205 - Isomorphic Strings
Problem Statement

Given two strings s and t, determine if they are isomorphic.

Two strings are isomorphic if:

Characters in s can be replaced to get t.
Each character maps to exactly one character.
No two different characters can map to the same character.
Examples
Input: s = "egg", t = "add"
Output: true
e → a
g → d
Input: s = "foo", t = "bar"
Output: false
f → b
o → a
o → r   ❌
Input: s = "ab", t = "aa"
Output: false
a → a
b → a   ❌
Approach: Last Occurrence Mapping
Intuition

Instead of storing actual character mappings, store the last occurrence position of each character.

If two characters are mapped together, they must always have appeared at the same previous position.

We use:

int[] mapS = new int[256];
int[] mapT = new int[256];
mapS[ch] → last position of character in string s
mapT[ch] → last position of character in string t
Key Observation

For every index i:

if(mapS[charS] != mapT[charT])
    return false;

If the previous occurrence positions are different, the mapping pattern is broken.

Therefore, the strings are not isomorphic.

Algorithm
Create two arrays of size 256.
Traverse both strings simultaneously.
For each character pair:
Compare their previous occurrence positions.
If different, return false.
Update both arrays with the current position.
If traversal completes, return true.
Java Solution
class Solution {
    public boolean isIsomorphic(String s, String t) {

        if (s == null || t == null || s.length() == 0 || t.length() == 0) {
            return false;
        }

        int[] mapS = new int[256];
        int[] mapT = new int[256];

        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {

            char charS = s.charAt(i);
            char charT = t.charAt(i);

            if (mapS[charS] != mapT[charT]) {
                return false;
            }

            mapS[charS] = i + 1;
            mapT[charT] = i + 1;
        }

        return true;
    }
}
Why i + 1?

Arrays are initialized with:

0

which means:

Character has not appeared yet.

If we stored:

mapS[charS] = i;

then:

Position 0

and

Never seen

would both be represented by 0.

To avoid this ambiguity, store:

mapS[charS] = i + 1;

Now:

0 = never seen
1 = first position
2 = second position
...
Dry Run
Input
s = "egg"
t = "add"
Initial State
mapS = all 0
mapT = all 0
i = 0
e → a

Check:

mapS[e] = 0
mapT[a] = 0

Equal ✅

Update:

mapS[e] = 1
mapT[a] = 1
i = 1
g → d

Check:

mapS[g] = 0
mapT[d] = 0

Equal ✅

Update:

mapS[g] = 2
mapT[d] = 2
i = 2
g → d

Check:

mapS[g] = 2
mapT[d] = 2

Equal ✅

Update:

mapS[g] = 3
mapT[d] = 3
Result
true
Example Where Mapping Fails
Input
s = "ab"
t = "aa"
i = 0
a → a

Store:

mapS[a] = 1
mapT[a] = 1
i = 1
b → a

Check:

mapS[b] = 0
mapT[a] = 1

Not equal ❌

Return:

false
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity
O(n)
Single traversal of both strings.
Space Complexity
O(1)
Two fixed-size arrays of length 256.
Key Takeaway

The core idea is:

Two characters can be mapped only if
their previous occurrence positions are identical.

Instead of storing actual mappings, we store the last seen position of each character and compare the patterns.

Pattern
Hashing / Character Mapping
Final Complexity
Metric	Complexity
Time	O(n)
Space	O(1)
